{"title_page": "Umaru Mutallab", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Alhaji]]\n| name               = Umaru Abdul Mutallab\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1939|12|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Katsina]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria| Northern Region]], <br>[[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Katsina]], Nigeria)\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| nationality        = [[Nigerian]]\n| education          = [[Barewa College]]<br>[[Achimota College]]<br>[[South West London College]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Banker\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = [[Katsina]]\n| party              = [[National Party of Nigeria]]\n| boards             = Chairman of [[Jaiz Bank]]<br>[[First Bank of Nigeria]]<br>[[Power Holding Company of Nigeria|NEPA]]<br>[[Agip|Nigeria Agip Oil]]\n| spouse             = 2\n| children           = 16; including [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]]\n| awards             = [[Order of the Niger|Nigerian Commander of the Order of the Niger]] <br> [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Italian Commander of the Order of Merit]]\n}}\n[[Alhaji]] '''Umaru Abdul Mutallab''' (born 15 December 1939) is a [[Nigeria|Nigerian]] businessman and financier, who served under the [[Nigerian military juntas of 1966\u201379 and 1983\u201398|military government]] of General [[Murtala Mohammed]] and [[Olusegun Obasanjo]].\n\nMutallab was described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"among Nigeria's richest and most prominent men\",<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/30/world/europe/30nigerian.html \"Terror Inquiry Looks at Suspect\u2019s Time in Britain\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 29 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009</ref> by ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' as being \"one of Nigeria's most prominent bankers\"<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/yemen/6911200/Detroit-terror-attack-timeline.html Rayner, Gordon, \"Detroit terror attack: timeline\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 30 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009</ref>, and by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as being \"one of the country's most respected businessmen\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/dec/27/gilded-life-of-plane-bomber \"Rich and privileged \u2013 the gilded life of would-be plane bomber,\"] [[The Guardian]], 27 December 2009. Retrieved 29 December 2009</ref> \n\nHis son, [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]] (the Christmas bomber) attempted to detonate [[plastic explosive]]s aboard [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]] on 25 December 2009. He is currently serving a 4 life terms sentence plus 50 years without parole at [[ADX Florence]], a [[supermax]] federal prison.\n\n==Biography==\nMutallab was born to the family of Abdul Mutallab Barade, an officer in the Funtua Works Dept. He lives in [[Funtua]], in Katsina State in Northern Nigeria,<ref name=Kennedy_Times_20091228>{{cite news|accessdate=28 December 2009\n|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/americas/article2001811.ece\n|title=Abdulmutallab's bomb plans began with classroom defence of 9/11\n|first=Dominic |last=Kennedy\n|work=[[The Times]] |date=28 December 2009 | location=London}}</ref> though reportedly the family owns homes in London and Ghana as well.<ref>\n[http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?c=Article_C&cid=1260258381266&pagename=Zone-English-News/NWELayout Oriyomi, Rafiu, \"Nigerian Terror Suspect (Profile)\"]{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, ''Islam Online'', 27 December 2009, accessed 29 December 2009\n</ref> The family owns at least three homes in Nigeria (in [[Abuja]], [[Funtua]], and [[Kaduna]]).<ref name= \"st  \">{{cite news| url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6974073.ece |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601124328/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6974073.ece |archivedate=1 June 2010  |last1=Newell  |first1=Claire |last2= Lamb |first2=Christina |last3=Ungoed-Thomas  |first3= Jon | last4=Gourlay  |first4=Chris  | last5=Dowling  |first5=Kevin  | last6=Tobin  |first6=Dominic  |date=3 January 2010  |title=Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab: one boy\u2019s journey to jihad |work= [[The Sunday Times]] |accessdate= 10 July 2015 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/31/bombing-suspect-abdulmutallab-nigeria-home | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Bombing suspect was pious pupil who shunned high life of the rich | first=Xan | last=Rice | date=31 December 2009 | accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nHe attended [[Barewa College]], Zaria, [[Achimota College]], [[Accra, Ghana]], and the [[London South Bank University|South West London College]], London.  He was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctoral degree]] by the [[Obafemi Awolowo University]], [[Ile-Ife]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n===Career===\nAfter completing his school certificate examinations in December 1959, Mutallab began work as a clerk with the firm of Pannell, Fitzpatrick and Company in [[Kaduna]] in January 1960. \n\nHe then travelled for further studies, returning to Nigeria in 1968, when he was appointed Chief Accountant of the [[Defence Industries Corporation of Nigeria]]. In 1971, he became the financial controller of the New Nigerian Development Company in Kaduna, before becoming the companies General Manager in 1975. \n\nMutallab was served as a government minister under General [[Murtala Mohammed]] and General [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] between 1975 to 1978.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2sxHAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Uma.ru+Mutallab%22&cd=10 ''New African development''], Volume 11, International Communications, African Development Magazine Ltd., 1977</ref> First as Federal Commissioner (''i.e.'', Minister) of Economic Development (1975),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-AG5AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=8 ''Africa''], Issues 41\u201352, Africa Journal Ltd., 1975</ref> he was relieved of the position after the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1976 military coup d'etat attempt]] that led to the death of General [[Murtala Mohammed]].<ref name=\"Seye\">Seye Kehinde. (22 January 1990). Umaru Mutallab: Man of Figures. ThisWeek, P. 29.</ref> However, he was later named the new Minister of Cooperatives and Supplies (1976).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hroMAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=13 ''Leadership in Nigeria (to date): an analysis''], C.A.N. Publicity, Northern Zone</ref> \n\nHe left the cabinet,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VNN1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=4 ''West Africa''], West Africa Pub. Co., ltd., 1982</ref> and was made executive vice-chairman, managing director, and CEO of the [[United Bank for Africa]] (UBA) (1978\u201388).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w2AEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=6 ''Sub-Saharan Africa report''], Issues 2757\u20132760'', p. 36, United States. Foreign Broadcast Information Service, 1983''</ref> He was a major financier of the [[1979 Nigerian presidential election|1979 presidential election]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HgR4AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=17 ''Ife social sciences review''], Volumes 6\u20138, University of Ife, Faculty of Social Sciences, Obafemi Awolowo University, Faculty of Social Sciences, 1983, accessed 29 December 2009</ref> which brought the [[National Party of Nigeria]] to power in the [[Second Nigerian Republic|Second Republic]] led by President [[Shehu Shagari]]. <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=IVXSAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=12 ''Newswatch''], Volume 6, p. 27, Newswatch Communications Ltd., 1987, accessed 29 December 2009</ref>\n\nMutallab has also served on the boards of directors of several companies, including Arewa Textile Limited, [[Power Holding Company of Nigeria|NEPA]], NACB, NCC, Nigeria [[Agip]] Oil, and Cement Company of Nigeria,\n\nFrom 1999 to 2009, he was the chairman of [[First Bank of Nigeria]] Plc, Nigeria's oldest and largest bank.<ref name=\"Sphere_200912272\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sphere.com/nation/article/nigerian-banker-alhaji-umaru-mutallab-fears-son-umar-farouk-abdul-mutallab-is-alleged-plane-attacker/19294494|title=Father of Terror Suspect Warned US Embassy|date=26 December 2009|work=Sphere|accessdate=29 December 2009|publisher=AOL News}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=RcLhAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=7 '' Newswatch''], Volume 41,&nbsp;Issues 15\u201325, p. 38, Newswatch Communications Ltd., 2005</ref> In 2009 was he chairman of several companies, including Impresit Bakolori Plc, Incar Nigeria Plc, and Spring Waters Nigeria Limited (SWAN).<ref>[http://www.champion.com.ng/index.php?news=24030 \"Mutallab, First Bank chairman retires\"], ''Champion Newspaper'', 16 December 2009, accessed 29 December 2009</ref> He is the major shareholder in Barade Holdings and Barumark Investment and Development Company.\n\nMuttalab played a major role in introducing [[Islamic banking]] into Nigeria, and he is the chairman of the Nigeria's first Islamic bank, [[Jaiz Bank]] International Plc, which was established in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/256633/1/dr-mutallab-told-us-embassy-umaru-was-planning-som.html |title = \"Dr. Mutallab told US Embassy Umaru was planning something\"- Family|date = 27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nMutallab is chairman of the Business Working Group of the Vision 20:2020 Committee in Nigeria, and president of the [[Barewa College|Old Boys Association of Barewa College]].<ref name=\"Vangard_2009-12-19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2009/12/19/yar%E2%80%99-adua-mutallab-urges-for-more-prayers/|title=Yar' Adua: Mutallab urges for more prayers|date=19 December 2009|work=Vanguard|accessdate=28 December 2009}}</ref> He is a Fellow of both the [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants]] (FCCA) and the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants of Nigeria]] (FCA).\n\nMutallab was awarded the title of Commander of the [[Order of the Niger]], one of Nigeria's highest honours.<ref>{{cite web |last=Morris |first=Loveday |date=2 January 2010 |url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/the-anatomy-of-a-suicide-bomber |title=The anatomy of a suicide bomber |work=The National |accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Umar Mutallab crop and contrast.png|thumb|150px|right|upright|[[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]], the suspected Northwest Airlines Flight 253 bomber]]\n\n==Personal life==\nThough very religious, Mutallab does not consider himself a religious extremist, explaining that he learned the capacity for tolerance while attending Barewa College which had students from many parts of the country and 'gives' a feeling of togetherness.<ref name=\"Seye\"/> He is also a member of the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a loose group of Nigerian [[businessmen]], [[civil servants]], [[intellectuals]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Nigeria]], who resided or conducted their activities in [[Kaduna]], the former capital of the region towards the end of the [[First Nigerian Republic|First Republic]]. Mutallab was a close friend and associate of the mafia's financier [[Hamza Rafindadi Zayyad|Hamza Zayyad]], who convinced him to take on accounting as a profession. \n\n===Son: Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab===\n{{Main|Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab}}\nMutallab had agreed in July 2009 to allow his son, [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]], the youngest of his 16 children and a son of the second of his two wives (who is from [[Yemen]]), to return to the [[San'a Institute for the Arabic Language]] in Yemen to study Arabic from August to September 2009.<ref name=\"AutoET-17\">Sengupta, Kim; Usborne, David (28 December 2009). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/nigerian-in-aircraft-attack-linked-to-london-mosque-1851452.html \"Nigerian in aircraft attack linked to London mosque\"], ''The Independent'', accessed 28 December 2009</ref><ref name=WP-20091228/><ref name= st/> His son apparently left the Institute after a month, while remaining in Yemen.<ref name= st/><ref name=WP-20091228/><ref>Elliott, Philip; and Baldor, Lolita C. [http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=9439201&page=3 \"Obama: US Intel Had Info Ahead of Airliner Attack\"], ABC News, 29 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009.</ref> In October, his son sent him a text message saying that he wanted to study ''[[sharia]]'' and Arabic in a seven-year course in Yemen.<ref name= st/> His father threatened to cut off his funding, whereupon his son said he was \"already getting everything for free\".<ref name= st/>\n\nMutallab reported to two [[CIA]] officers at the [[US Embassy]] in [[Abuja]], [[Nigeria]], on 19 November 2009,<ref name=WP-20091228>{{cite news|author1=DeYoung, Karen  |author2=Leahy, Michael |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Uninvestigated terrorism warning about Detroit suspect called not unusual|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/27/AR2009122700279.html|date=28 December 2009|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=CBSNews_20091228>{{cite news|accessdate=28 December 2009 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/12/28/world/main6029782.shtml\n|title=Abdulmutallab Shocks Family, Friends |publisher=CBS News |date=28 December 2009}}</ref> regarding his son's \"extreme religious views\", and told the embassy that he might be in Yemen.<ref name= st/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5g576mMIiaVSpiw-wwX9rZ7uECILA |title=Obama orders review of US no-fly lists |agency=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=28 December 2009 }}</ref><ref name=NYT-20091227>{{cite news|author1=Lipton, Eric  |author2=Shane, Scott |lastauthoramp=yes |title=More Questions on Why Terror Suspect Was Not Stopped|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/28/us/28terror.html|date=27 December 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> His son's name was added in November 2009 to the US's 550,000-name [[Terrorist Identities Datamart Environment]], a database of the US [[National Counterterrorism Center]].<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,581193,00.html |title=Father of Terror Suspect Reportedly Warned U.S. About Son |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=28 December 2009 |date=26 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228092002/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,581193,00.html |archive-date=28 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> His US visa was not revoked.<ref name= st/> On 25 December 2009, Umar was implicated in the attempted bombing of [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]].<ref name=\"AutoET-17\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Nigeria|Biography}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120455/http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/sunday/index.php/news/11331-mutallab-an-accomplished-banker Mutallab, an accomplished banker]\n* [http://www.summitreports.com/nigeria1/fbn.htm Bank profile]\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.firstbanknigeria.com/aboutfbn/au_bod.asp |title=Bank board website |access-date=26 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609050923/http://www.firstbanknigeria.com/aboutfbn/au_bod.asp |archive-date=9 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* Egene, Goddy, \"[http://allafrica.com/stories/200912280866.html Mutallab: Profile in Courage],\" ''[[ThisDay]]'' via [[AllAfrica.com]], 28 December 2009\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mutallab, Umaru}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Federal ministers of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Nigerian bankers]]\n[[Category:Nigerian economists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian accountants]]\n[[Category:Nigerian Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Katsina]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the Niger]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Barewa College alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Achimota School]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Alhaji]]\n| name               = Umaru Abdul Mutallab\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1939|12|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Katsina]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria| Northern Region]], <br>[[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Katsina]], Nigeria)\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| nationality        = [[Nigerian]]\n| education          = [[Barewa College]]<br>[[Achimota College]]<br>[[South West London College]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = Banker\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = [[Katsina]]\n| party              = [[National Party of Nigeria]]\n| boards             = Chairman of [[Jaiz Bank]]<br>[[First Bank of Nigeria]]<br>[[Power Holding Company of Nigeria|NEPA]]<br>[[Agip|Nigeria Agip Oil]]\n| spouse             = 2\n| children           = 16; including [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]]\n| awards             = [[Order of the Niger|Nigerian Commander of the Order of the Niger]] <br> [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Italian Commander of the Order of Merit]]\n}}\n[[Alhaji]] '''Umaru Abdul Mutallab''' (born 15 December 1939) is a [[Nigeria|Nigerian]] businessman and financier, who served under the [[Nigerian military juntas of 1966\u201379 and 1983\u201398|military government]] of General [[Murtala Mohammed]] and [[Olusegun Obasanjo]].\n\nMutallab was described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as \"among Nigeria's richest and most prominent men\",<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/30/world/europe/30nigerian.html \"Terror Inquiry Looks at Suspect\u2019s Time in Britain\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 29 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009</ref> by ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' as being \"one of Nigeria's most prominent bankers\"<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/yemen/6911200/Detroit-terror-attack-timeline.html Rayner, Gordon, \"Detroit terror attack: timeline\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'', 30 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009</ref>, and by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as being \"one of the country's most respected businessmen\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/dec/27/gilded-life-of-plane-bomber \"Rich and privileged \u2013 the gilded life of would-be plane bomber,\"] [[The Guardian]], 27 December 2009. Retrieved 29 December 2009</ref> \n\nHis son, [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]] (the Christmas bomber) attempted to detonate [[plastic explosive]]s aboard [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]] on 25 December 2009. He is currently serving a 4 life terms sentence plus 50 years without parole at [[ADX Florence]], a [[supermax]] federal prison.\n\n==Biography==\nMutallab was born to the family of Abdul Mutallab Barade, an officer in the Funtua Works Dept. He lives in [[Funtua]], in Katsina State in Northern Nigeria,<ref name=Kennedy_Times_20091228>{{cite news|accessdate=28 December 2009\n|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/americas/article2001811.ece\n|title=Abdulmutallab's bomb plans began with classroom defence of 9/11\n|first=Dominic |last=Kennedy\n|work=[[The Times]] |date=28 December 2009 | location=London}}</ref> though reportedly the family owns homes in London and Ghana as well.<ref>\n[http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?c=Article_C&cid=1260258381266&pagename=Zone-English-News/NWELayout Oriyomi, Rafiu, \"Nigerian Terror Suspect (Profile)\"]{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=March 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}, ''Islam Online'', 27 December 2009, accessed 29 December 2009\n</ref> The family owns at least three homes in Nigeria (in [[Abuja]], [[Funtua]], and [[Kaduna]]).<ref name= \"st  \">{{cite news| url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6974073.ece |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601124328/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6974073.ece |archivedate=1 June 2010  |last1=Newell  |first1=Claire |last2= Lamb |first2=Christina |last3=Ungoed-Thomas  |first3= Jon | last4=Gourlay  |first4=Chris  | last5=Dowling  |first5=Kevin  | last6=Tobin  |first6=Dominic  |date=3 January 2010  |title=Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab: one boy\u2019s journey to jihad |work= [[The Sunday Times]] |accessdate= 10 July 2015 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/31/bombing-suspect-abdulmutallab-nigeria-home | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Bombing suspect was pious pupil who shunned high life of the rich | first=Xan | last=Rice | date=31 December 2009 | accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nHe attended [[Barewa College]], Zaria, [[Achimota College]], [[Accra, Ghana]], and the [[London South Bank University|South West London College]], London.  He was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honorary doctoral degree]] by the [[Obafemi Awolowo University]], [[Ile-Ife]].{{citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n===Career===\nAfter completing his school certificate examinations in December 1959, Mutallab began work as a clerk with the firm of Pannell, Fitzpatrick and Company in [[Kaduna]] in January 1960. \n\nHe then travelled for further studies, returning to Nigeria in 1968, when he was appointed Chief Accountant of the [[Defence Industries Corporation of Nigeria]]. In 1971, he became the financial controller of the New Nigerian Development Company in Kaduna, before becoming the companies General Manager in 1975. \n\nMutallab was became a member of Nigeria's [[Federal Executive Council (Nigeria)|Federal Executive Council]] (1976\u201378).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2sxHAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Uma.ru+Mutallab%22&cd=10 ''New African development''], Volume 11, International Communications, African Development Magazine Ltd., 1977</ref> First as Federal Commissioner (''i.e.'', Minister) of Economic Development (1975),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=-AG5AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=8 ''Africa''], Issues 41\u201352, Africa Journal Ltd., 1975</ref> he was relieved of the position after the [[1976 Nigerian coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1976 military coup d'etat attempt]] that led to the death of General [[Murtala Mohammed]].<ref name=\"Seye\">Seye Kehinde. (22 January 1990). Umaru Mutallab: Man of Figures. ThisWeek, P. 29.</ref> However, he was later named the new Minister of Cooperatives and Supplies (1976).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hroMAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=13 ''Leadership in Nigeria (to date): an analysis''], C.A.N. Publicity, Northern Zone</ref> \n\nHe left the cabinet,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VNN1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=4 ''West Africa''], West Africa Pub. Co., ltd., 1982</ref> and was made executive vice-chairman, managing director, and CEO of the [[United Bank for Africa]] (UBA) (1978\u201388).<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w2AEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=6 ''Sub-Saharan Africa report''], Issues 2757\u20132760'', p. 36, United States. Foreign Broadcast Information Service, 1983''</ref> He was a major financier of the [[1979 Nigerian presidential election|1979 presidential election]],<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HgR4AAAAIAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=17 ''Ife social sciences review''], Volumes 6\u20138, University of Ife, Faculty of Social Sciences, Obafemi Awolowo University, Faculty of Social Sciences, 1983, accessed 29 December 2009</ref> which brought the [[National Party of Nigeria]] to power in the [[Second Nigerian Republic|Second Republic]] led by President [[Shehu Shagari]]. <ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=IVXSAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=12 ''Newswatch''], Volume 6, p. 27, Newswatch Communications Ltd., 1987, accessed 29 December 2009</ref>\n\nMutallab has also served on the boards of directors of several companies, including Arewa Textile Limited, [[Power Holding Company of Nigeria|NEPA]], NACB, NCC, Nigeria [[Agip]] Oil, and Cement Company of Nigeria,\n\nFrom 1999 to 2009, he was the chairman of [[First Bank of Nigeria]] Plc, Nigeria's oldest and largest bank.<ref name=\"Sphere_200912272\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sphere.com/nation/article/nigerian-banker-alhaji-umaru-mutallab-fears-son-umar-farouk-abdul-mutallab-is-alleged-plane-attacker/19294494|title=Father of Terror Suspect Warned US Embassy|date=26 December 2009|work=Sphere|accessdate=29 December 2009|publisher=AOL News}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=RcLhAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&dq=%22Umaru+Mutallab%22&cd=7 '' Newswatch''], Volume 41,&nbsp;Issues 15\u201325, p. 38, Newswatch Communications Ltd., 2005</ref> In 2009 was he chairman of several companies, including Impresit Bakolori Plc, Incar Nigeria Plc, and Spring Waters Nigeria Limited (SWAN).<ref>[http://www.champion.com.ng/index.php?news=24030 \"Mutallab, First Bank chairman retires\"], ''Champion Newspaper'', 16 December 2009, accessed 29 December 2009</ref> He is the major shareholder in Barade Holdings and Barumark Investment and Development Company.\n\nMuttalab played a major role in introducing [[Islamic banking]] into Nigeria, and he is the chairman of the Nigeria's first Islamic bank, [[Jaiz Bank]] International Plc, which was established in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/256633/1/dr-mutallab-told-us-embassy-umaru-was-planning-som.html |title = \"Dr. Mutallab told US Embassy Umaru was planning something\"- Family|date = 27 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nMutallab is chairman of the Business Working Group of the Vision 20:2020 Committee in Nigeria, and president of the [[Barewa College|Old Boys Association of Barewa College]].<ref name=\"Vangard_2009-12-19\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2009/12/19/yar%E2%80%99-adua-mutallab-urges-for-more-prayers/|title=Yar' Adua: Mutallab urges for more prayers|date=19 December 2009|work=Vanguard|accessdate=28 December 2009}}</ref> He is a Fellow of both the [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants]] (FCCA) and the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants of Nigeria]] (FCA).\n\nMutallab was awarded the title of Commander of the [[Order of the Niger]], one of Nigeria's highest honours.<ref>{{cite web |last=Morris |first=Loveday |date=2 January 2010 |url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/the-anatomy-of-a-suicide-bomber |title=The anatomy of a suicide bomber |work=The National |accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Umar Mutallab crop and contrast.png|thumb|150px|right|upright|[[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]], the suspected Northwest Airlines Flight 253 bomber]]\n\n==Personal life==\nThough very religious, Mutallab does not consider himself a religious extremist, explaining that he learned the capacity for tolerance while attending Barewa College which had students from many parts of the country and 'gives' a feeling of togetherness.<ref name=\"Seye\"/> He is also a member of the [[Kaduna Mafia]], a loose group of Nigerian [[businessmen]], [[civil servants]], [[intellectuals]] and [[Nigerian Armed Forces|military officers]] from [[Northern Nigeria]], who resided or conducted their activities in [[Kaduna]], the former capital of the region towards the end of the [[First Nigerian Republic|First Republic]]. Mutallab was a close friend and associate of the mafia's financier [[Hamza Rafindadi Zayyad|Hamza Zayyad]], who convinced him to take on accounting as a profession. \n\n===Son: Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab===\n{{Main|Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab}}\nMutallab had agreed in July 2009 to allow his son, [[Umar Farouk Abdulmutallab]], the youngest of his 16 children and a son of the second of his two wives (who is from [[Yemen]]), to return to the [[San'a Institute for the Arabic Language]] in Yemen to study Arabic from August to September 2009.<ref name=\"AutoET-17\">Sengupta, Kim; Usborne, David (28 December 2009). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/nigerian-in-aircraft-attack-linked-to-london-mosque-1851452.html \"Nigerian in aircraft attack linked to London mosque\"], ''The Independent'', accessed 28 December 2009</ref><ref name=WP-20091228/><ref name= st/> His son apparently left the Institute after a month, while remaining in Yemen.<ref name= st/><ref name=WP-20091228/><ref>Elliott, Philip; and Baldor, Lolita C. [http://abcnews.go.com/US/wirestory?id=9439201&page=3 \"Obama: US Intel Had Info Ahead of Airliner Attack\"], ABC News, 29 December 2009. Retrieved 30 December 2009.</ref> In October, his son sent him a text message saying that he wanted to study ''[[sharia]]'' and Arabic in a seven-year course in Yemen.<ref name= st/> His father threatened to cut off his funding, whereupon his son said he was \"already getting everything for free\".<ref name= st/>\n\nMutallab reported to two [[CIA]] officers at the [[US Embassy]] in [[Abuja]], [[Nigeria]], on 19 November 2009,<ref name=WP-20091228>{{cite news|author1=DeYoung, Karen  |author2=Leahy, Michael |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Uninvestigated terrorism warning about Detroit suspect called not unusual|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/27/AR2009122700279.html|date=28 December 2009|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=CBSNews_20091228>{{cite news|accessdate=28 December 2009 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/12/28/world/main6029782.shtml\n|title=Abdulmutallab Shocks Family, Friends |publisher=CBS News |date=28 December 2009}}</ref> regarding his son's \"extreme religious views\", and told the embassy that he might be in Yemen.<ref name= st/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5g576mMIiaVSpiw-wwX9rZ7uECILA |title=Obama orders review of US no-fly lists |agency=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=28 December 2009 }}</ref><ref name=NYT-20091227>{{cite news|author1=Lipton, Eric  |author2=Shane, Scott |lastauthoramp=yes |title=More Questions on Why Terror Suspect Was Not Stopped|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/28/us/28terror.html|date=27 December 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=27 December 2009}}</ref> His son's name was added in November 2009 to the US's 550,000-name [[Terrorist Identities Datamart Environment]], a database of the US [[National Counterterrorism Center]].<ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,581193,00.html |title=Father of Terror Suspect Reportedly Warned U.S. About Son |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=28 December 2009 |date=26 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228092002/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,581193,00.html |archive-date=28 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> His US visa was not revoked.<ref name= st/> On 25 December 2009, Umar was implicated in the attempted bombing of [[Northwest Airlines Flight 253]].<ref name=\"AutoET-17\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Nigeria|Biography}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120455/http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/sunday/index.php/news/11331-mutallab-an-accomplished-banker